{"title_page": "Barnbougle Castle", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox Military Structure\n|name=Barnbougle Castle\n|location=[[Dalmeny]], Scotland\n|coordinates = {{coord|55.9924348|-3.3342916|type:landmark|display=inline}}\n|image=Barnbougle02.JPG\n|image_size=300px\n|caption=Barnbougle Castle on the Firth of Forth, with Edinburgh in the distance\n|map_type = Edinburgh\n|map_relief= \n|map_caption = Location within City of Edinburgh\n|type=\n|built=13th century\n|builder=\n|materials=\n|used=\n|condition=Rebuilt 1881, still in use\n|ownership=[[Earl of Rosebery]]\n|open_to_public=\n|controlledby=\n}}\n'''Barnbougle Castle''' is a much-altered [[tower house]] on the southern shore of the [[Firth of Forth]], between [[Cramond]] and [[South Queensferry|Queensferry]], and within the parish of [[Dalmeny]]. It lies within the [[Earl of Rosebery]]'s estate, just northwest of [[Dalmeny House]]. Although its history goes back to the 13th century, the present castle is the result of rebuilding in 1881 by the [[Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery|5th Earl of Rosebery]], who served as Prime Minister from 1894\u20131895.\n\n==Etymology==\nOlder forms of the name include Barnbughall, Barbogle, Parnbogalle, and Pronbugele. This comes from the [[Common Brittonic|British]] ''brinn bugel'', meaning 'shepherd's hill', or ''bar an bugel'', 'shepherd's hill top', or alternatively ''pren bugel'', 'shepherd's tree'.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Bethany |last=Fox |title=The P-Celtic Place-Names of North-East England and South-East Scotland |journal=The Heroic Age |volume=10 |year=2007 |url=http://www.heroicage.org/issues/10/fox.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |first=Bethany |last=Fox |title=The P-Celtic Place-Names of North-East England and South-East Scotland Appendix: Discussion of Individual Names |journal=The Heroic Age |volume=10 |year=2007 |url=http://www.heroicage.org/issues/10/fox.html}}</ref> All these names likely refer to the high ground which rises immediately behind the shore, which overlook the grazings around the mouth of the Cockle Burn.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Place Names of Edinburgh: their Origins and History|date=2002|last=Harris|first=Stuart|location=London & Edinburgh|publisher=Steve Savage Publishers Ltd|isbn=1904246060}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Barnbougle01.JPG|thumb|300px|left|Barnbougle seen from the south west]]\nThe first building at Barnbougle was a thirteenth-century [[tower house]], constructed by the [[House of Mowbray|Mowbray]]s, a [[Normans|Norman]] family who were also lords of Dalmeny and [[Inverkeithing]].<ref name=LBR>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=LB5548|desc=Dalmeny House, Barnbougle Castle, including balustrade and sundial|cat=A|access-date=1 April 2019}}</ref> The laird of Barnbougle in 1586 was a supporter of [[Mary, Queen of Scots]], his wife was a sister of [[William Kirkcaldy of Grange]] and their daughters served Mary in England, Gillis betrothed to her apothecary and Barbara married Gilbert Curll, the secretary.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 8 (Edinburgh, 1914), p. 330.</ref>\n\nIn 1615 the Mowbrays sold Barnbougle to [[Thomas Hamilton, 1st Earl of Haddington|Sir Thomas Hamilton]], afterwards [[Earl of Haddington]]. It was sold again in 1662, by Sir Thomas' grandson, to [[Archibald Primrose, Lord Carrington|Sir Archibald Primrose of Carrington]], a senior judge who became [[Lord Justice General]] of Scotland in 1676. Sir Archibald's eldest son by his second marriage, also [[Archibald Primrose, 1st Earl of Rosebery|Archibald Primrose]], was created Earl of Rosebery in 1703, and Barnbougle became the family seat. At some point during the 17th century, the original tower house was rebuilt or replaced.<ref name=canmore/>\n\nIn 1774, a plan for rebuilding the castle was drawn up by the architect [[Robert Adam]]. This proposal was for a triangular building, with the original tower at its seaward corner, but it was never executed. By the early 19th century, the castle had become dilapidated, and a wave supposedly washed into the dining room during supper.<ref name=LBR/> The [[Archibald Primrose, 4th Earl of Rosebery|4th Earl of Rosebery]] had [[Dalmeny House]] constructed on the estate, and the family moved in on completion in 1817. Barnbougle was used to store explosives, and after being damaged in an accidental explosion, it was subsequently left as a ruin.<ref name=LBR/>\n\nIn 1881 the castle was entirely reconstructed and extended according to plans by James Maitland Wardrop, of Wardrop & Reid, in the [[Scots Baronial]] style. The older fabric of the north side was incorporated into the new building.<ref name=canmore>{{cite web |url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/50443/edinburgh-barnbougle-castle |title=Barnbougle Castle |work=Canmore |publisher=Historic Environment Scotland |accessdate=23 March 2017}}</ref> It was primarily built to house the private library of Archibald, 5th Earl of Rosebery (1847\u20131929), who became Prime Minister in 1894. Lord Rosebery practised his speeches here, in a purpose-built gallery hall.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dalmeny.co.uk/dalmeny-house/the-shore-walk |accessdate=23 March 2017 |publisher=Dalmeny Estate |title=Shore Walk}}</ref> Barnbougle remains a part of the Dalmeny Estate, and is still the property of the Rosebery family. It is a category A [[listed building]].<ref name=LBR/>\n\n==Description==\nThe castle is built on a projecting rock terrace.  It incorporates some of the fabric of the original castle on the north and east sides, but is mainly a late-nineteenth century construction.<ref name=canmore/>  There are three storeys and an attic; the building is rubble, dressed with [[ashlar]] sandstone. Features include [[crowstep]] gables, [[bartizan]]s (small turrets) with water spouts on the two western corners, and a [[crenellated]] parapet.  A panel on the east wall is inscribed \"Remove Not The Ancient Landmark Which Thy Fathers Have Set. [[Book of Proverbs|Proverbs XXII.28]]\".<ref name=LBR/> A {{convert|2.4|m|adj=on}} high [[scottish sundial|obelisk sundial]] stands in the castle garden, having been moved there in 1890.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/50404/edinburgh-barnbougle-castle-sundial |title=Barnbougle Castle, Sundial |work=Canmore |publisher=Historic Environment Scotland |accessdate=23 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Traditions ==\nThe antiquary William Wallace Fyfe recorded, in 1851, a legend associated with Barnbougle and nearby [[Hound Point]]. He relates that \"whenever the death of any of its [Barnbougle's] lords is about to occur, the unwonted apparition of a black man, accompanied by a hound, appears upon the point, and winds from his bugle the death-note of the baron. Hence the origin of the ancient name of ''Bar'n-bugle''.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Fyfe |first=William Wallace |title=Summer life on land and water at South Queensferry |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6ZsHAAAAQAAJ |pages=156\u2013158 |publisher=Oliver & Boyd |year=1851 }}</ref> Fyfe took the story as inspiration for a poem relating the adventures of \"Sir Roger Mowbray\" and his faithful dog on [[crusades|Crusade]] in the Holy Land, culminating in Sir Roger's death and closing with the words:\n:And ever when Barnbougle's lords\n:Are parting this scene below\n:Come hound and ghost to this haunted coast\n:With death notes winding slow.\n\nA number of variations on this legend have been recorded, including versions where the baying of a hound, rather than a trumpet, precedes a death.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://queensferry-at-war.weebly.com/local-legends-and-facts/first-of-many-snippets |title=Local Legends and Facts |publisher=Queensferry History Group |accessdate=23 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170323234224/http://queensferry-at-war.weebly.com/local-legends-and-facts/first-of-many-snippets |archive-date=23 March 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Barnbougle Castle}}\n*[http://www.roseberyvenues.co.uk Rosebery Venues web site]\n\n{{coord|55.9922|N|3.3337|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Castles in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Category A listed buildings in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Listed castles in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Reportedly haunted locations in Edinburgh]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox Military Structure\n|name=Barnbougle Castle\n|location=[[Dalmeny]], Scotland\n|coordinates = {{coord|55.9924348|-3.3342916|type:landmark|display=inline}}\n|image=Barnbougle02.JPG\n|image_size=300px\n|caption=Barnbougle Castle on the Firth of Forth, with Edinburgh in the distance\n|map_type = Edinburgh\n|map_relief= \n|map_caption = Location within City of Edinburgh\n|type=\n|built=13th century\n|builder=\n|materials=\n|used=\n|condition=Rebuilt 1881, still in use\n|ownership=[[Earl of Rosebery]]\n|open_to_public=\n|controlledby=\n}}\n'''Barnbougle Castle''' is a much-altered [[tower house]] on the southern shore of the [[Firth of Forth]], between [[Cramond]] and [[South Queensferry|Queensferry]], and within the parish of [[Dalmeny]]. It lies within the [[Earl of Rosebery]]'s estate, just northwest of [[Dalmeny House]]. Although its history goes back to the 13th century, the present castle is the result of rebuilding in 1881 by the [[Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery|5th Earl of Rosebery]], who served as Prime Minister from 1894\u20131895.\n\n==Etymology==\nOlder forms of the name include Barnbughall, Barbogle, Parnbogalle, and Pronbugele. This comes from the [[Common Brittonic|British]] ''brinn bugel'', meaning 'shepherd's hill', or ''bar an bugel'', 'shepherd's hill top', or alternatively ''pren bugel'', 'shepherd's tree'.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Bethany |last=Fox |title=The P-Celtic Place-Names of North-East England and South-East Scotland |journal=The Heroic Age |volume=10 |year=2007 |url=http://www.heroicage.org/issues/10/fox.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |first=Bethany |last=Fox |title=The P-Celtic Place-Names of North-East England and South-East Scotland Appendix: Discussion of Individual Names |journal=The Heroic Age |volume=10 |year=2007 |url=http://www.heroicage.org/issues/10/fox.html}}</ref> All these names likely refer to the high ground which rises immediately behind the shore, which overlook the grazings around the mouth of the Cockle Burn.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Place Names of Edinburgh: their Origins and History|date=2002|last=Harris|first=Stuart|location=London & Edinburgh|publisher=Steve Savage Publishers Ltd|isbn=1904246060}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Barnbougle01.JPG|thumb|300px|left|Barnbougle seen from the south west]]\nThe first building at Barnbougle was a thirteenth-century [[tower house]], constructed by the [[House of Mowbray|Mowbray]]s, a [[Normans|Norman]] family who were also lords of Dalmeny and [[Inverkeithing]].<ref name=LBR>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=LB5548|desc=Dalmeny House, Barnbougle Castle, including balustrade and sundial|cat=A|access-date=1 April 2019}}</ref> The laird of Barnbougle in 1586 was supporter of [[Mary, Queen of Scots]], his wife was a sister of [[William Kirkcaldy of Grange]] and their daughters served Mary in England, Gillis betrothed to her apothecary and Barbara married Gilbert Curll, the secretary.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 8 (Edinburgh, 1914), p. 330.</ref>\n\nIn 1615 the Mowbrays sold Barnbougle to [[Thomas Hamilton, 1st Earl of Haddington|Sir Thomas Hamilton]], afterwards [[Earl of Haddington]]. It was sold again in 1662, by Sir Thomas' grandson, to [[Archibald Primrose, Lord Carrington|Sir Archibald Primrose of Carrington]], a senior judge who became [[Lord Justice General]] of Scotland in 1676. Sir Archibald's eldest son by his second marriage, also [[Archibald Primrose, 1st Earl of Rosebery|Archibald Primrose]], was created Earl of Rosebery in 1703, and Barnbougle became the family seat. At some point during the 17th century, the original tower house was rebuilt or replaced.<ref name=canmore/>\n\nIn 1774, a plan for rebuilding the castle was drawn up by the architect [[Robert Adam]]. This proposal was for a triangular building, with the original tower at its seaward corner, but it was never executed. By the early 19th century, the castle had become dilapidated, and a wave supposedly washed into the dining room during supper.<ref name=LBR/> The [[Archibald Primrose, 4th Earl of Rosebery|4th Earl of Rosebery]] had [[Dalmeny House]] constructed on the estate, and the family moved in on completion in 1817. Barnbougle was used to store explosives, and after being damaged in an accidental explosion, it was subsequently left as a ruin.<ref name=LBR/>\n\nIn 1881 the castle was entirely reconstructed and extended according to plans by James Maitland Wardrop, of Wardrop & Reid, in the [[Scots Baronial]] style. The older fabric of the north side was incorporated into the new building.<ref name=canmore>{{cite web |url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/50443/edinburgh-barnbougle-castle |title=Barnbougle Castle |work=Canmore |publisher=Historic Environment Scotland |accessdate=23 March 2017}}</ref> It was primarily built to house the private library of Archibald, 5th Earl of Rosebery (1847\u20131929), who became Prime Minister in 1894. Lord Rosebery practised his speeches here, in a purpose-built gallery hall.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dalmeny.co.uk/dalmeny-house/the-shore-walk |accessdate=23 March 2017 |publisher=Dalmeny Estate |title=Shore Walk}}</ref> Barnbougle remains a part of the Dalmeny Estate, and is still the property of the Rosebery family. It is a category A [[listed building]].<ref name=LBR/>\n\n==Description==\nThe castle is built on a projecting rock terrace.  It incorporates some of the fabric of the original castle on the north and east sides, but is mainly a late-nineteenth century construction.<ref name=canmore/>  There are three storeys and an attic; the building is rubble, dressed with [[ashlar]] sandstone. Features include [[crowstep]] gables, [[bartizan]]s (small turrets) with water spouts on the two western corners, and a [[crenellated]] parapet.  A panel on the east wall is inscribed \"Remove Not The Ancient Landmark Which Thy Fathers Have Set. [[Book of Proverbs|Proverbs XXII.28]]\".<ref name=LBR/> A {{convert|2.4|m|adj=on}} high [[scottish sundial|obelisk sundial]] stands in the castle garden, having been moved there in 1890.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/50404/edinburgh-barnbougle-castle-sundial |title=Barnbougle Castle, Sundial |work=Canmore |publisher=Historic Environment Scotland |accessdate=23 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Traditions ==\nThe antiquary William Wallace Fyfe recorded, in 1851, a legend associated with Barnbougle and nearby [[Hound Point]]. He relates that \"whenever the death of any of its [Barnbougle's] lords is about to occur, the unwonted apparition of a black man, accompanied by a hound, appears upon the point, and winds from his bugle the death-note of the baron. Hence the origin of the ancient name of ''Bar'n-bugle''.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Fyfe |first=William Wallace |title=Summer life on land and water at South Queensferry |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6ZsHAAAAQAAJ |pages=156\u2013158 |publisher=Oliver & Boyd |year=1851 }}</ref> Fyfe took the story as inspiration for a poem relating the adventures of \"Sir Roger Mowbray\" and his faithful dog on [[crusades|Crusade]] in the Holy Land, culminating in Sir Roger's death and closing with the words:\n:And ever when Barnbougle's lords\n:Are parting this scene below\n:Come hound and ghost to this haunted coast\n:With death notes winding slow.\n\nA number of variations on this legend have been recorded, including versions where the baying of a hound, rather than a trumpet, precedes a death.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://queensferry-at-war.weebly.com/local-legends-and-facts/first-of-many-snippets |title=Local Legends and Facts |publisher=Queensferry History Group |accessdate=23 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170323234224/http://queensferry-at-war.weebly.com/local-legends-and-facts/first-of-many-snippets |archive-date=23 March 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Barnbougle Castle}}\n*[http://www.roseberyvenues.co.uk Rosebery Venues web site]\n\n{{coord|55.9922|N|3.3337|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Castles in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Category A listed buildings in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Listed castles in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Reportedly haunted locations in Edinburgh]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barnbougle_Castle"}
